tspan.tspan: Trithereon's clerics are rugged individualists, never afraid to question authority. Those in
cities instruct commoners in self-defense and recruit like-minded rogues and rangers for
the cause of individual liberty. Those in rural areas act as scouts or spies against despotic
lords or murderous non-humans. Both sorts keep close watch on Lawful religions lest they
become too powerful.
Those who venerate Trithereon strive for liberty for themselves and others. His clerics
work fervently to end tyrannical regimes or free those in slavery. Followers of Trithereon
must often travel in secrecy to avoid harassment from those in positions of power. It is
said by some that no ruler ever feels entirely secure when a shrine to Trithereon lies
within his borders.
Trithereon (CG) is a foe of evil and oppression
"All deserve life and the ability to choose their own place in the world. Whomever would
place others in shackles, or control them with oppressive laws, must be toppled."
"Train the common folk to defend themselves and their property should another wish to
take their freedoms."
"If you are wronged, you have the right to exact vengeance yourself, especially if none will
help you."
Trithereon clearly has a different outlook from Ul; Libertarianism versus quasi-communism. Because
of this, worship is considered subversive and kept very private and this is the only real secret that
Kaliska was keeping in Ul before her leave.
Where the two intersect, in Kaliska, is in taking action. Kaliska was driven batty by Ul's isolationism &
the decision to sacrifice unknowing "good" citizens. She is not a cleric; not a prophet or full devotee.
She is a vessel. Her blend of worship doesn't accept the view of calling for total liberty from the state.
But rather, liberty of thought, of agency. To allow each a choice of accepting or rejecting, at least
once, that which the state asks of you. [Kind of a
Rumspinga
myth]
To that end, her morals are to fiercely reject foreign power, support self-determination, punish
deceivers, and yet maintain absolute fealty to one's (chosen) community. It's a balance of the two
competing dogmas, but a razor-thin delicate one. Time and events may tell if she tips one way or
another.
